# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alfred-bulltop-stormalong
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Folktales have also been misused to perpetuate negative stereotypes about the African American community, from minstrel shows to academic journals.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] One of these figures is High John de Conqueror.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] He often symbolized empowerment for newly freed slaves, It was said that if they needed him, his spirit resided in a local root.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Other common figures in African American folktales include Anansi, Br'er Rabbit, and Uncle Monday.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Many folktales are unique to African-American culture, while African, European, and Native American tales influenced others.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] In the present, the impact of African American folklore is apparent in Hip-hop music, where themes like gangsters and pimps are influenced by the "badman" and "trickster" archetypes.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] African-American folktales are a storytelling tradition rooted in Africa.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] These folktales are a testament to a rich oral tradition that spread when Africans were brought to the Americas as slaves.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Most African-American folktales fall into one of eight categories of tales: origin stories, trickery and trouble, triumph over natural or supernatural evils, comic or heartwarming, God and the devil, life lessons, ghosts and spirits, slaves and their slave-owners.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Many revolve around anthropomorphic animals with the same morals and shortcomings as humans, providing a sense of relatability.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] New tales voice the African experience in the Americas; however, many tales still maintain the traditional style and tell of their African roots.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Although many of the original stories evolved since Africans were brought to the Americas as slaves, their meanings and life lessons have remained the same.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Enslaved Black people frequently crafted stories featuring animals such as rabbits, foxes, bears, wolves, turtles, snakes, and possums, imbuing them with the traits of the individuals they encountered in the unfamiliar setting of the plantation.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] African-American tales place emphasis on beginnings and transformations, whether focused on a character, an event, or the creation of the world.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Some examples of origin stories include "How Jackal Became an Outcast" and "Terrapin's Magic Dipper and Whip", which respectively explain the solitary nature of jackals and why turtles have shells.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Tricksters in folk stories are commonly amoral characters, whether human or animal who succeed through deception and exploiting the weaknesses of others.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] They use their wits to resolve conflict and achieve their goals.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Two examples of African-American tricksters are Br'er Rabbit and Anansi.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Tricksters in African-American folktales take a comedic approach and contain underlying themes of inequality, compared to other folktales that label their tricksters as menaces.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] The National Humanities Center notes that trickster stories "contain serious commentary on the inequities of existence in a country where the promises of democracy were denied to a large portion of the citizenry, a pattern that becomes even clearer in the literary adaptations of trickster figures".
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] African-American folktales do not always contain an actual trickster.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Sometimes, they operate around themes of trickery tactics.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] For example, Charles Chesnutt collected a series of stories and created *The Conjure Woman* (1899).
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] One of the trickster's tactics in the story is "how an enslaved man is spared being sent from one plantation to another by having his wife, who is a conjure woman, turns him into a tree.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] The trickery works until a local sawmill selects that particular tree to cut".
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] In other tales, personified animals try to imitate the trickster, though it backfires on them.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] An example is in *Crawling Into the Elephant's Belly,* in which Yawarri, an anteater, follows Anansi, the trickster, and blackmails him to be brought to the king's elephants.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Yawarri's family is starving, and he is upset at Anansi because of all the elephant meat Anansi is eating, which is the king's property.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] After jumping the wall, Anansi instructs Yawarri on how to get inside the elephant, telling him only to take a small piece of meat from the elephant so the king will not notice.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] However, since Yawarri is starving, he eats at the inside of the elephant until it dies.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] At sunrise, the king finds him in the beast's belly and kills him.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] This shows how an ordinary citizen can get wrapped up in the scheme of a trickster.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Other tales that display this theme are "Why They Name the Stories for Anansi" and "A License to Steal", although there are many more.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Comic and heartwarming African-American folktales "stimulate the imagination with wonders and are told to remind us of the perils and the possibilities." The stories are about heroes, heroines, villains, and fools.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] African folklore is a means to hand down traditions and duties through generations.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Stories are often passed down orally at gatherings by groups of children and elders.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] This type of gathering was known as "*Tales by Midnight"*and contained cultural lessons that prepared children for their future.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] These anthropomorphic animals made the stories compelling to young children, and included singing, dancing, or themes such as greed, honesty, and loyalty.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] One example used by generations of storytellers for African children is the "Tale of The Midnight Goat Thief", which originated in Zimbabwe, and is a tale of misplaced trust.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] A hare betrays the trust of a loyal baboon, framing him for the death of a goat.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] After the baboon's friend, a jackal, hears about what happened to him, he tries to replicate what the hare did to the baboon to get revenge.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] However, the hare outwits the jackal and finds a way to counter his actions.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] When the sun rises, the jackal is caught red-handed with the blood he planned to frame the hare with.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] The moral of the story is to be loyal and honest, and to not copy the ways of the cunning, as they may outwit you.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] African-American tales of ghosts and spirits were commonly told of a spook or "haint" or "haunt," referring to repeated visits by ghosts or spirits that keep one awake at night.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] The story "Possessed of Two Spirits" recounts a personal experience in conjuring magic powers in both the living and the spiritual world, a common trope in African-American folklore.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] The story "Married to a Boar Hog" emerged during the American Revolution against the British.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] The story is of a young woman who marries a supernatural entity, such as a boar, and is saved from her disease, such as leprosy, clubfoot, or yaws.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] "Married to a Boar Hog" is passed down from British Caribbean slaves in reference to their African origin and the hardships they endured.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] African-American folktales show how the world was formed and the foundations of morality.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Supernatural conflicts between God and the Devil are often the main focus of these tales.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] However, man versus man, and slave versus master are also popular disputes.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] There is typically a "negotiator" in these tales who is actively trying to persuade "the judge" to side with their position.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] However, if the judge, or God, does not like the outcome of the situation, they will often invoke a countermeasure to bring order to the situation.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] In these tales, the God, or gods, are inherently good and do not invoke wrath upon the people, even if the subject veers off the path of righteousness.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Additionally, there is often a transaction between God and man in these tales, one in which God is willing to help man, but only if the man is "offering sacrifices and performing rites and ceremonies in a manner acceptable to the god".
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] An example of one of these tales is "Never Seen His Equal".
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] The opening dialogue of this tale discusses how only man has seen his equal, but God has not.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] It then describes how the devil opposes God and, in Genesis, ultimately manifests himself as a serpent to trick Adam and Eve who reside in the Garden.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] This tells the story of the fall of man through Adam and Eve eating the forbidden fruit when tempted by the serpent, and how women now have to have pain in childbirth and men have to work for survival.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Although many slaves during this time could not read or write, they could recite folktales as a method of relaying information to each other, sharing vital knowledge that would aid in their survival.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] In African-American tales, the depiction of slavery often employs a rhetoric that may appear unconventional by modern standards, as the language transmitted across generations deviates from the typical racial narrative.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] When confronted with the harsh reality of slavery, African-American folktales served as a method to cope with the situation and document their history of slavery in America.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] An example of a work that conveys the African-American slave experience in America is *The Conjure Woman*.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] This collection of short stories, written by African-American author Charles W.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Chestnutt, deals with the theme of racial identity from the perspective of a freed slave.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Chesnutt's tales depict the challenges encountered by freed slaves in the post-war South, offering a reflective view on the difficulties of those who were marginalized during this period.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Chesnutt's language surrounding African-American folklore derived from the standards of the racial narrative of his era.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] By using vernacular language, Chesnutt was able to deviate from the racial norms and formulate a new, more valorized message of folk heroes.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Chesnutt writes "on the other side" of standard racial narratives, effectively refuting them by evoking a different kind of "racial project" in his fictional work.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] The book *Mojo Workin': The Old African American Hoodoo System* discusses the folk spirit High John de Conqueror, whose spirit lies within the "John the Conqueror root" in the Hoodoo tradition.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] In African-American folk stories, High John de Conqueror was an African prince who was kidnapped from Africa and enslaved in the United States.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] He was a trickster and used his charm to deceive and outsmart his slaveholders.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] After the American Civil War, before High John de Conqueror returned to Africa, he told the newly freed slaves that if they ever needed his spirit for freedom, his spirit would be at rest within a root they could use.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] According to some scholars, the origin of High John de Conqueror may have originated from African male deities such as Elegua, who is a trickster spirit in West Africa.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Zora Neale Hurston documented some history about High John de Conqueror from her discussions with African Americans in the South in her book, *The Sanctified Church*.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Some African Americans believed High John de Conqueror freed the slaves, and that President Abraham Lincoln and the Civil War did not bring freedom for Black people.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Aunt Shady Anne Sutton, a woman interviewed by Hurston, affirms this belief: "These young Negroes reads they books and talk about the war freeing the Negroes, by Aye Lord!
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] 'Course, the war was a lot of help, but how come the war took place?
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] John de Conqueror had done put it into the white folks to give us our freedom".
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] In consonance with Sutton's statement, it had been the teachings by High John de Conqueror that assisted in the freedom of slaves, as opposed to the efforts by Lincoln and the actions taken during the Civil War.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] The root also provided protection against whippings from slaveholders and provided freedom from chattel slavery.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Frederick Douglass' experience with the root supports this belief, as it is said he avoided being whipped and beaten by a slave-breaker because he had it in possession.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] A second instance of the root's impact is told through the eyes of Henry Bibb, who was born into slavery, as he used the root to protect himself by chewing and spitting it towards his enslaver.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Flying Africans of legend escaped enslavement by a magical flight over the ocean back to Africa.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Novelist Toni Morrison makes references to African American spirituality in her literature, and her novel *Song of Solomon*, published in 1977, tells the story of the character Milkman, an African American in search of his African ancestors.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Milkman lived in the North but returned to the South in search of his ancestry.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] By the end of the book, Milkman learns he comes from a family of African medicine people and gained his ancestral powers and his soul flew back to Africa after he died.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] The legend may have been inspired by a historical event in Georgia.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] In 1803, a slave ship landed on the coast of Georgia in St.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Simons Island with captive Africans from Nigeria with a cargo of Igbo people.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] The Igbo people chose suicide than a lifetime of slavery by walking into the swamp and drowning.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] The most common saying from slaves was, "I would rather live on my feet than die on my knees".
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] This location became known as Igbo Landing in Georgia.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] According to African American folklore, the souls of the Igbos that committed suicide flew back to Africa.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] In African-American folklore, there is a story about a girl named Sukey meeting a mermaid named Mama Jo.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Mama Jo in the story helps and protects Sukey and financially supports her by giving her gold coins.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] This story comes from the belief in Simbi spirits from the Bakongo people of West-Central Africa, who came to the United States during the trans-Atlantic slave trade.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] In Africa, Simbi nature spirits protect and provide riches to their followers.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] In West-Central Africa, there are folk stories of people meeting mermaids.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Among the Gullah Geechee people in the Carolina Lowcountry and Sea Islands is a children's story called *Sukey and the Mermaid* written by Robert D.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] In the African diaspora, there are Afro-American folk stories of a little girl meeting a mermaid.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] During the era of slavery, Simbi folk stories in enslaved black communities provided hope from enslavement.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] It was believed that Simbi spirits help guide freedom seekers (runaway slaves) to freedom or to maroon communities during their escape from slavery on the Underground Railroad, because Simbi spirits reside in nature.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] In African-American folklore, Uncle Monday was a conjurer, medicine man, and shapeshifter from Africa enslaved in the Southern United States.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Uncle Monday escaped from slavery on the Underground Railroad and traveled through South Carolina and Georgia and made his final stop in Florida living amongst the Seminole people and Black Seminoles.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] He led a resistance movement against enslavement using his conjure powers.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] In the folktale, Seminole people and Black Seminoles beat their drums and Uncle Monday danced to the rhythms of Seminole and African music and turned into an alligator.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] After turning into an alligator, Uncle Monday went to the swamp waters and the other alligators followed him.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] In his alligator form, he and the others defeated the slaveholders.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] This folktale added historical accounts of the alliance between the Seminole people and Black Seminoles and their resistance movement against enslavement, and fictional stories about magic and shapeshifting.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] During the 19th century, the white community began to use African-American folklore as a propaganda tool for disseminating Black stereotypes and erroneous views, such as characterizing the African-American Vernacular as strange and grammatically unstructured.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] The advent of these ideologies coincided with the rise of the minstrel shows, whose performers and producers would compose songs and books in the "black dialect" with a view to boosting their reputation.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] This practice is exemplified by the famous minstrel artist Thomas D.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Rice who popularized the character Jim Crow.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Through songs, dances, and other forms of African-American folklore, he and other minstrels cemented harmful portrayals of African Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Some Maafa apologists used these stories to push racist ideologies.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Some academic journals have appeared to challenge this rhetoric, as these authors displayed bias and utilized stories that showed negative stereotypes.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] In 1877, journalist William Owens stated that African-American traits have "a fitness" to the characteristics portrayed in African folklore.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Abrahams perpetuated these in his book *Afro-American folktales*.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] He pushed the point that African-American folklore is an "immoral reflection" of African religions and "animal tales are a reflection of African's childlike mannerisms".
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] African-American folklore was predominantly used for guidance and protection.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Some say the folklore acts as a "secret language".
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Folklore like "Wade in the Water", "Down by the River", and "Old Bill Rolling Pin", were used to help people escaping enslavement alert each other to danger like dogs or people patrolling.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Folklore's impact also translates to today, as some tropes are seen in modern-day Hip-Hop.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] The trickster trope originated as a way to display enslaved people's wit over slave masters.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] After emancipation, this trope transformed into badman, which reflected the new ways of life.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] The badman was viewed as more of an outlaw.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] In the badman trope existed a sub-genre called Stagolee, which was based on a pimp named Lee Shelton, who killed a man after gambling and losing his hat.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Stagolee's story was told in many forms, from blues to jazz, and made its way to a style called "Toast".
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Toast is "a story told in the first person that was recited in verse".
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] The rappers would use this trope to embody themselves, and it gave them charisma.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] This translates to the beginning of Hip-Hop and artists like Snoop Dogg, utilized these story-telling methods.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Stagolee's influence also translated to clothing similar to Hip-Hop.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] In the late 1800s, black men wore the Stetson Hat worn by Stagolee as a status symbol.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] This commodification can be seen in Hip-hop today through cars, girls, baggy pants, etc.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Some artists still use characteristics of the original trickster archetype as well.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Common themes in hip-hop, such as hyper-sexuality, vulgarity, hyper-masculinity, and revenge, are seen through lyrics of rap artists like Da Brat to Juvenile and heavily used in Tricker-related folklore like Anansi.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] The 1946 Film *Song of the South* adapted Joel Chandler Harris's publication of African-American folktales collected under the title Uncle Remus and His Tales of Br'er Rabbit The film received poor reviews for of its portrayal of Uncle Remus and for being unengaging.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] "Glorification of slavery" is how NAACP executive Walter White described it.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Despite these flaws, *Song of the South* won an Academy Award for best original song with "Zip-A-Dee-Doo-Dah", while James Baskett, the actor in the role of Uncle Remus, received an Honorary Oscar.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Director and cartoonist Frederick Bean "Tex" Avery was known to invoke ethnic stereotypes in his films.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] He would notably use the Bebop trope in his animations.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] The use of Bebop can be seen through one of his most famous characters, Bugs Bunny from Looney Tunes.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Bugs Bunny's personality borrows from the mannerisms of Bebop musicians.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] One of these characteristics can be seen in the animation titled, A Wild Hare (1940).
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] When Bugs allows Elmer Fudd, to shoot at him, displaying "aloofness in the face of violence", commonly associated with Bebop.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Bug's popular catchphrase "What's up, Doc" shows "coolness" to the threat posed by Elmer Fudd.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Some have argued that his catchphrase is similar to black people during the mid-1900s, like "You don't scare me".
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] In numerous superhero films and cartoons, there are mentions of various African American Folklore Characters.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] For example, Anansi the Spider has been seen in *Static Shock*, *The Amazing Spider-Man*, and *American Gods*.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] John Henry is also seen in animated shows like *The Grim Adventures of Billy & Mandy* Season 6, *Teen Titans Go!* Season 5, and a modern-day movie adaptation starring Terry Crews called *John Henry*.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-folktales] Writer Zaire Lanier incorporated folk tales and creatures from African-American and Southern history, and original tales, in the fictionalized south in *South of Midnight*.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] African-American history began in the 16th century, when mainly West African and Central African slave traders sold African artisans, farmers, and warriors to European slave traders, who transported them across the Atlantic to the Western Hemisphere.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] They were sold as slaves to European colonists and put to work on plantations, particularly in the southern colonies.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] A few were able to achieve freedom through manumission or escape, and founded independent communities before and during the American Revolution.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] After the United States was founded in 1783, most American Black people continued to be enslaved, primarily in the American South, with four million enslaved people only liberated after the Northern victory over the South in the Civil War of 1861 to 1865.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] During Reconstruction, African Americans gained citizenship and adult-males the right to vote; however, due to widespread belief in White supremacy, they were treated as second-class citizens and soon effectively disenfranchised in the South.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] These circumstances changed due to participation in the military conflicts of the United States, substantial migration out of the South, the elimination of legal racial segregation, and the civil rights movement which sought political and social freedom.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] However, racism against African Americans and racial socioeconomic disparity remain a problem into the 21st century.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] In the 20th and 21st centuries, immigration has played an increasingly significant role in the African-American community.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Black population were immigrants, and 20% were either immigrants or the children of immigrants.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] While some Black immigrants or their children may also come to identify as African American, the majority of first-generation immigrants do not, preferring to identify with their nation of origin.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Most African Americans are of West African and coastal Central African ancestry, with varying amounts of Western European and Native American ancestry (see §Genetics).
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] African-American culture has had a significant influence on worldwide culture, making numerous contributions to the English language, literature, politics, cuisine, sports, and music.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] The African-American contribution to popular music is so profound that most American popular music, including gospel, blues, jazz, rock and roll, R&B, soul, funk, disco, hip-hop, and house has its origins either partially or entirely in the African-American community.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] The vast majority of those who were enslaved and transported in the transatlantic slave trade were people from several Central and West African ethnic groups.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] They had been captured directly by European slave traders in coastal raids, or captured and sold by West African slave traders or by half-European "merchant princes" to European slave traders, who brought them to the Americas.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] The first African slaves in what is now the United States arrived in the early 16th century.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Africans were among Juan Ponce de León's 1513 voyage that landed in what would become Spanish Florida, and enslaved Africans arrived around the same time to Spanish Puerto Rico.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Africans also came via Santo Domingo in the Caribbean to the San Miguel de Gualdape colony (most likely located in the Winyah Bay area of present-day South Carolina), founded by Spanish explorer Lucas Vázquez de Ayllón in 1526.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] The ill-fated colony was almost immediately disrupted by a fight over leadership, during which the slaves revolted and fled the colony to seek refuge among local Native Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] De Ayllón and many of the colonists died shortly afterward, due to an epidemic and the colony was abandoned.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] The settlers and the slaves who had not escaped returned to the Island of Hispaniola, whence they had come.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] The enslaved explorer Esteban arrived in Florida with the Narváez expedition in 1528, a journey that first landed in Santo Domingo and later traveled into Spanish Texas and the Southwest before ending in Mexico.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] The marriage between Luisa de Abrego, a free Black domestic servant from Seville, and Miguel Rodríguez, a White Segovian conquistador in 1565 in St.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Augustine (Spanish Florida), is the first known and recorded Christian marriage anywhere in what is now the continental United States.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] The first recorded Africans in English America (including most of the future United States) were "20 and odd negroes" who arrived in Jamestown, Virginia via Cape Comfort in August 1619 as indentured servants.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] As many Virginian settlers began to die from harsh conditions, more and more Africans were brought to work as laborers.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] An indentured servant (who could be White or Black) would work for several years (usually four to seven) without wages.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] The status of indentured servants in early Virginia and Maryland was similar to slavery.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Servants could be bought, sold, or leased, and they could be physically beaten for disobedience or attempting to running away.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Unlike slaves, they were freed after their term of service expired or if their freedom was purchased.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Their children did not inherit their status, and on their release from contract they received "a year's provision of corn, double apparel, tools necessary", and a small cash payment called "freedom dues".
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Africans could legally raise crops and cattle to purchase their freedom.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] They raised families, married other Africans and sometimes intermarried with Native Americans or European settlers.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] By the 1640s and 1650s, several African families owned farms around Jamestown, and some became wealthy by colonial standards and purchased indentured servants of their own.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] In 1640, the Virginia General Court recorded the earliest documentation of lifetime slavery when they sentenced John Punch, a Negro, to lifetime servitude under his master Hugh Gwyn, for running away.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] In Spanish Florida, some Spanish married or had unions with Pensacola, Creek or African women, both enslaved and free, and their descendants created a mixed-race population of mestizos and mulattos.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] The Spanish encouraged slaves from the colony of Georgia to come to Florida as a refuge, promising freedom in exchange for conversion to Catholicism.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] King Charles II issued a royal proclamation freeing all slaves who fled to Spanish Florida and accepted conversion and baptism.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Augustine, but escaped slaves also reached Pensacola.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Augustine had mustered an all-Black militia unit defending Spanish Florida as early as 1683.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] One of the Dutch African arrivals, Anthony Johnson, would later own one of the first Black "slaves", John Casor, resulting from the court ruling of a civil case.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] The popular conception of a race-based slave system did not fully develop until the 18th century.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] The Dutch West India Company introduced slavery in 1625 with the importation of eleven Black slaves into New Amsterdam (present-day New York City).
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] All the colony's slaves, however, were freed upon its surrender to the English.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Massachusetts was the first English colony to legally recognize slavery in 1641.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] In 1662, Virginia passed a law that children of enslaved women would take the status of the mother, rather than that of the father, as was the case under common law.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] This legal principle was called *partus sequitur ventrum*.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] By an act of 1699, Virginia ordered the deportation of all free Blacks, effectively defining all people of African descent who remained in the colony as slaves.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] In 1670, the colonial assembly passed a law prohibiting free and baptized Blacks (and Native Americans) from purchasing Christians (in this act meaning White Europeans) but allowing them to buy people "of their owne nation".
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] In Spanish Louisiana, although there was no movement toward abolition of the African slave trade, Spanish rule introduced a new law called *coartación*, which allowed slaves to buy their freedom, and that of others.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Although some did not have the money to do so, government measures on slavery enabled the existence of many free Blacks.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] This caused problems to the Spaniards with the French creoles (French who had settled in New France) who had also populated Spanish Louisiana.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] The French creoles cited that measure as one of the system's worst elements.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] First established in South Carolina in 1704, groups of armed White men—slave patrols—were formed to monitor enslaved Black people.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Their function was to police slaves, especially fugitives.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Slave owners feared that slaves might organize revolts or slave rebellions, so state militias were formed to provide a military command structure and discipline within the slave patrols.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] These patrols were used to detect, encounter, and crush any organized slave meetings which might lead to revolts or rebellions.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] The earliest African American congregations and churches were organized before 1800 in both northern and southern cities following the Great Awakening.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] By 1775, Africans made up 20% of the population in the American colonies, which made them the second-largest ethnic group after English Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] During the 1770s, Africans, both enslaved and free, helped rebellious American colonists secure their independence by defeating the British in the American Revolutionary War.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Blacks played a role in both sides in the American Revolution.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Activists in the Patriot cause included James Armistead, Prince Whipple, and Oliver Cromwell.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Around 15,000 Black Loyalists left with the British after the war, most of them ending up as free Black people in England or its colonies, such as the Black Nova Scotians and the Sierra Leone Creole people.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] In the Spanish Louisiana, Governor Bernardo de Gálvez organized Spanish free Black men into two militia companies to defend New Orleans during the American Revolution.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] They fought in the 1779 battle in which Spain captured Baton Rouge from the British.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Gálvez also commanded them in campaigns against the British outposts in Mobile, Alabama, and Pensacola, Florida.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] He recruited slaves for the militia by pledging to free anyone who was seriously wounded and promised to secure a low price for *coartación* (buy their freedom and that of others) for those who received lesser wounds.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] During the 1790s, Governor Francisco Luis Héctor, baron of Carondelet reinforced local fortifications and recruit even more free Black men for the militia.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Carondelet doubled the number of free Black men who served, creating two more militia companies—one made up of Black members and the other of pardo (mixed race).
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Serving in the militia brought free Black men one step closer to equality with Whites, allowing them, for example, the right to carry arms and boosting their earning power.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] However, actually these privileges distanced free Black men from enslaved Blacks and encouraged them to identify with Whites.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Slavery had been tacitly enshrined in the US Constitution through provisions such as Article I, Section 2, Clause 3, commonly known as the 3/5 compromise.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Due to the restrictions of Section 9, Clause 1, Congress was unable to pass an Act Prohibiting Importation of Slaves until 1807.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Fugitive slave laws (derived from the Fugitive Slave Clause of the Constitution—Article IV, Section 2, Clause 3) were passed by Congress in both 1793 and 1850, guaranteeing the right of a slaveholder to recover an escaped slave anywhere within the US.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Slave owners, who viewed enslaved people as property, ensured that it became a federal crime to aid or assist those who had fled slavery or to interfere with their capture.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] By that time, slavery, which almost exclusively targeted Black people, had become the most critical and contentious political issue in the Antebellum United States, repeatedly sparking crises and conflicts.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Among these were the Missouri Compromise, the Compromise of 1850, the infamous Dred Scott decision, and John Brown's raid on Harpers Ferry.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Prior to the Civil War, eight serving presidents had owned slaves, a practice that was legally protected under the US Constitution.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] By 1860, the number of enslaved Black people in the US had grown to between 3.5 and 4.4 million, largely as a result of the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] In addition, 488,000–500,000 Black people lived free around the country, with legislated limits imposed upon them in addition to "unconquerable prejudice" from Whites according to Henry Clay.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] In response to these conditions, some free Black people chose to leave the US and emigrate to Liberia in West Africa.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Liberia had been established in 1821 as a settlement by the American Colonization Society (ACS), with many abolitionist members of the ACS believing Black Americans would have greater opportunities for freedom and equality in Africa than they would in the US.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Slaves not only represented a significant financial investment for their owners, but they also played a crucial role in producing the country's most valuable product and export: cotton.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Enslaved people were instrumental in the construction of several prominent structures such as, the United States Capitol, the White House and other Washington, D.C.–based buildings.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Similar building projects existed in the slave states.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] By 1815, the domestic slave trade had become a significant and major economic activity in the United States, continuing to flourish until the 1860s.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Historians estimate that nearly one million individuals were subjected to this forced migration, which was often referred to as a new "Middle Passage".
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] The historian Ira Berlin described this internal forced migration of enslaved people as the "central event" in the life of a slave during the period between the American Revolution and the Civil War.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Berlin emphasized that whether enslaved individuals were directly uprooted or lived in constant fear that they or their families would be involuntarily relocated, "the massive deportation traumatized Black people" throughout the US.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] As a result of this large-scale forced movement, countless individuals lost their connection to families and clans, and many ethnic Africans lost their knowledge of varying tribal origins in Africa.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Emigration of free Blacks to their continent of origin had been proposed since the Revolutionary war.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] After Haiti became independent, it tried to recruit African Americans to migrate there after it re-established trade relations with the United States.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] The Haitian Union was a group formed to promote relations between the countries.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] After riots against Blacks in Cincinnati, its Black community sponsored founding of the Wilberforce Colony, an initially successful settlement of African American immigrants to Canada.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] The colony was one of the first such independent political entities.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] It lasted for a number of decades and provided a destination for about 200 Black families emigrating from a number of locations in the United States.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] In 1863, during the American Civil War, President Abraham Lincoln signed the Emancipation Proclamation.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] The proclamation declared that all slaves in Confederate-held territory were free.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Advancing Union troops enforced the proclamation, with Texas being the last state to be emancipated, in 1865.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Slavery in a few border states continued until the ratification of the Thirteenth Amendment in December 1865.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] While the Naturalization Act of 1790 limited US citizenship to Whites only, the 14th Amendment (1868) gave Black people citizenship, and the 15th Amendment (1870) gave Black men the right to vote.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] African Americans quickly set up congregations for themselves, as well as schools and community/civic associations, to have space away from White control or oversight.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] While the post-war Reconstruction era was initially a time of progress for African Americans, that period ended in 1876.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] By the late 1890s, Southern states enacted Jim Crow laws to enforce racial segregation and disenfranchisement.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Segregation was now imposed with Jim Crow laws, using signs used to show Blacks where they could legally walk, talk, drink, rest, or eat.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] For those places that were racially mixed, non-Whites had to wait until all White customers were dealt with.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Most African Americans obeyed the Jim Crow laws, to avoid racially motivated violence.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] To maintain self-esteem and dignity, African Americans such as Anthony Overton and Mary McLeod Bethune continued to build their own schools, churches, banks, social clubs, and other businesses.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] In the last decade of the 19th century, racially discriminatory laws and racial violence aimed at African Americans began to mushroom in the United States, a period often referred to as the "nadir of American race relations".
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] These discriminatory acts included racial segregation—upheld by the United States Supreme Court decision in *Plessy v.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] The desperate conditions of African Americans in the South sparked the Great Migration during the first half of the 20th century which led to a growing African American community in Northern and Western United States.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] The rapid influx of Blacks disturbed the racial balance within Northern and Western cities, exacerbating hostility between both Blacks and Whites in the two regions.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] The Red Summer of 1919 was marked by hundreds of deaths and higher casualties across the US as a result of race riots that occurred in more than three dozen cities, such as the Chicago race riot of 1919 and the Omaha race riot of 1919.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Overall, Blacks in Northern and Western cities experienced systemic discrimination in a plethora of aspects of life.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Within employment, economic opportunities for Blacks were routed to the lowest-status and restrictive in potential mobility.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] While many Whites defended their space with violence, intimidation, or legal tactics toward African Americans, many other Whites migrated to more racially homogeneous suburban or exurban regions, a process known as White flight.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Despite discrimination, drawing cards for leaving the hopelessness in the South were the growth of African American institutions and communities in Northern cities.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Institutions included Black oriented organizations (e.g., Urban League, NAACP), churches, businesses, and newspapers, as well as successes in the development in African American intellectual culture, music, and popular culture (e.g., Harlem Renaissance, Chicago Black Renaissance).
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] The Cotton Club in Harlem was a Whites-only establishment, with Blacks (such as Duke Ellington) allowed to perform, but to a White audience.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Black Americans also found a new ground for political power in Northern cities, without the enforced disabilities of Jim Crow.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] By the 1950s, the civil rights movement was gaining momentum.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] A 1955 lynching that sparked public outrage about injustice was that of Emmett Till, a 14-year-old boy from Chicago.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Spending the summer with relatives in Money, Mississippi, Till was killed for allegedly having wolf-whistled at a White woman.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Till had been badly beaten, one of his eyes was gouged out, and he was shot in the head.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] The visceral response to his mother's decision to have an open-casket funeral mobilized the Black community throughout the US.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Vann Newkirk wrote "the trial of his killers became a pageant illuminating the tyranny of White supremacy".
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] The state of Mississippi tried two defendants, but they were speedily acquitted by an all-White jury.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] The March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom and the conditions which brought it into being are credited with putting pressure on presidents John F.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] By 1966, the emergence of the Black Power movement, which lasted from 1966 to 1975, expanded upon the aims of the civil rights movement to include economic and political self-sufficiency, and freedom from White authority.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] During the post-war period, many African Americans continued to be economically disadvantaged relative to other Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Average Black income stood at 54 percent of that of White workers in 1947, and 55 percent in 1962.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] In 1965, 43 percent of all Black families fell into the poverty bracket, earning under $3,000 (equivalent to $30,649 in 2025) a year.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] The 1960s saw improvements in the social and economic conditions of many Black Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] From 1965 to 1969, Black family income rose from 54 to 60 percent of White family income.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] In 1968, 23 percent of Black families earned under $3,000 (equivalent to $27,775 in 2025) a year, compared with 41 percent in 1960.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] In 1965, 19 percent of Black Americans had incomes equal to the national median, a proportion that rose to 27 percent by 1967.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] In 1960, the median level of education for Blacks had been 10.8 years, and by the late 1960s, the figure rose to 12.2 years, half a year behind the median for Whites.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Politically and economically, African Americans have made substantial strides during the post–civil rights era.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] In 1967, Thurgood Marshall became the first African American Supreme Court Justice.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] In 1968, Shirley Chisholm became the first Black woman elected to the US Congress.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] In 1989, Douglas Wilder became the first African American elected governor in US history.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Clarence Thomas succeeded Marshall to become the second African American Supreme Court Justice in 1991.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] In 1992, Carol Moseley-Braun of Illinois became the first African American woman elected to the US Senate.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] There were 8,936 Black officeholders in the United States in 2000, showing a net increase of 7,467 since 1970.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] In 2005, the number of Africans immigrating to the United States, in a single year, surpassed the peak number who were involuntarily brought to the United States during the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] On November 4, 2008, Democratic Senator Barack Obama—the son of a White American mother and a Kenyan father—defeated Republican Senator John McCain to become the first African American to be elected president.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] At least 95 percent of African American voters voted for Obama.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] He also received overwhelming support from young and educated Whites, a majority of Asians, and Hispanics, picking up a number of new states in the Democratic electoral column.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Obama lost the overall White vote, although he won a larger proportion of White votes than any previous non-incumbent Democratic presidential candidate since Jimmy Carter.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] Obama was reelected for a second and final term, by a similar margin on November 6, 2012.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] In 2021, Kamala Harris, the daughter of a Jamaican father and Indian mother, became the first woman, the first African American, and the first Asian American to serve as Vice President of the United States.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p01] In June 2021, Juneteenth, a day which commemorates the end of slavery in the US, became a federal holiday.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In 1790, when the first US census was taken, Africans (including slaves and free people) numbered about 760,000—about 19.3% of the population.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In 1860, at the start of the Civil War, the African American population had increased to 4.4 million, but the percentage rate dropped to 14% of the overall population of the country.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The vast majority were slaves, with only 488,000 counted as "freemen".
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] By 1900, the Black population had doubled and reached 8.8 million.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In 1910, about 90% of African Americans lived in the South.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Large numbers began migrating north looking for better job opportunities and living conditions, and to escape Jim Crow laws and racial violence.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The Great Migration, as it was called, spanned the 1890s to the 1970s.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] From 1916 through the 1960s, more than six million Black people moved north.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] But in the 1970s and 1980s, that trend reversed, with more African Americans moving south to the Sun Belt than leaving it.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] By 1990, the African American population reached about 30 million and represented 12% of the US population, roughly the same proportion as in 1900.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] At the time of the 2000 US census, 54.8% of African Americans lived in the South.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In that year, 17.6% of African Americans lived in the Northeast and 18.7% in the Midwest, while only 8.9% lived in the Western states.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The west does have a sizable Black population in certain areas, however.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] California, the nation's most populous state, has the fifth-largest African American population, only behind New York, Texas, Georgia, and Florida.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] According to the 2000 census, approximately 2.05% of African Americans identified as Hispanic or Latino in origin, many of whom may be of Brazilian, Puerto Rican, Dominican, Cuban, Haitian, or other Latin American descent.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The only self-reported *ancestral* groups larger than African Americans are the Irish and Germans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] According to the 2010 census, nearly 3% of people who self-identified as Black had recent ancestors who immigrated from another country.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Self-reported non-Hispanic Black immigrants from the Caribbean, mostly from Jamaica and Haiti, represented 0.9% of the US population, at 2.6 million.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Self-reported Black immigrants from sub-Saharan Africa also represented 0.9%, at about 2.8 million.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Additionally, self-identified Black Hispanics represented 0.4% of the United States population, at about 1.2 million people, largely found within the Puerto Rican and Dominican communities.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Self-reported Black immigrants hailing from other countries in the Americas, such as Brazil and Canada, as well as several European countries, represented less than 0.1% of the population.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Mixed-race Hispanic and non-Hispanic Americans who identified as being part Black, represented 0.9% of the population.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Of the 12.6% of United States residents who identified as Black, around 10.3% were "native Black American" or ethnic African Americans, who are direct descendants of West/Central Africans brought to the US as slaves.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] These individuals make up well over 80% of all Blacks in the country.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] When including people of mixed-race origin, about 13.5% of the US population self-identified as Black or "mixed with Black".
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] However, according to the US Census Bureau, evidence from the 2000 census indicates that many African and Caribbean immigrant ethnic groups do not identify as "Black, African Am., or Negro".
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Instead, they wrote in their own respective ethnic groups in the "Some Other Race" write-in entry.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] As a result, the census bureau devised a new, separate "African American" ethnic group category in 2010 for ethnic African Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Nigerian Americans and Ethiopian Americans were the most reported sub-Saharan African groups in the United States.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In the 2020 census, the African American population was undercounted at an estimated rate of 3.3%, up from 2.1% in 2010.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Texas has the largest African American population by state with approximately four million.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Followed by Texas is Florida, with 3.8 million, and Georgia, with 3.6 million.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Mississippi is the state with the highest African American share of the population at 39%.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Followed by Mississippi is Louisiana at 34%, and Georgia at 32%.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] After 100 years of African Americans leaving the south in large numbers seeking better opportunities and treatment in the west and north, a movement known as the Great Migration, there is now a reverse trend, called the New Great Migration.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] As with the earlier Great Migration, the New Great Migration is primarily directed toward cities and large urban areas, such as Charlotte, Houston, Dallas, Fort Worth, Huntsville, Raleigh, Tampa, San Antonio, New Orleans, Memphis, Nashville, Jacksonville, and so forth.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] A growing percentage of African Americans from the west and north are migrating to the southern region of the US for economic and cultural reasons.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In 2020, New York City, Chicago, and Los Angeles metropolitan areas had the highest decline in African Americans, while Atlanta, Dallas, and Houston had the highest increase respectively.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Despite recent declines, as of 2020, the New York City metropolitan area still has the largest African American metropolitan population in the United States and the only to have over three million African Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Among cities of 100,000 or more, South Fulton, Georgia had the highest percentage of Black residents of any large US city in 2020, with 93%.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Claiborne County, Mississippi is the Blackest county in the U.S. at 87% Black in 2020.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Cook County, Illinois has the largest Black population in the U.S. with 1,185,601 Black residents in 2020.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The nation's most affluent community with an African American majority resides in View Park–Windsor Hills, California, with an annual median household income of $159,618 and median home price of about $1.5 million in 2025.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Additionally, there is a significant affluent Black presence in the southern Chicago suburbs of Cook County, Illinois.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In 2006, Queens County, New York was the only county with a population of 65,000 or more where African Americans had a higher median household income than White Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Seatack, Virginia is currently the oldest African American community in the United States.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] It survives today with a vibrant and active civic community.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] During slavery, anti-literacy laws were enacted in the US that prohibited education for Black people.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Slave owners saw literacy as a threat to the institution of slavery.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] When slavery was finally abolished in 1865, public educational systems were expanding across the country.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] By 1870, around seventy-four institutions in the south provided a form of advanced education for African American students.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] By 1900, over a hundred programs at these schools provided training for Black professionals, including teachers.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Many of the students at Fisk University, including the young W.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Du Bois, taught school during the summers to support their studies.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] African Americans were very concerned to provide quality education for their children, but White supremacy limited their ability to participate in educational policymaking on the political level.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] State governments soon moved to undermine their citizenship by restricting their right to vote.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] By the late 1870s, Blacks were disenfranchised and segregated across the American South.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] White politicians in Mississippi and other states withheld financial resources and supplies from Black schools.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Nevertheless, the presence of Black teachers, and their engagement with their communities both inside and outside the classroom, ensured that Black students had access to education despite these external constraints.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] During World War II, demands for unity and racial tolerance on the home front provided an opening for the first Black history curriculum in the country.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] For example, during the early 1940s, Madeline Morgan, a Black teacher in the Chicago public schools, created a curriculum for students in grades one through eight highlighting the contributions of Black people to the history of the United States.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] At the close of the war, Chicago's Board of Education downgraded the curriculum's status from mandatory to optional.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Predominantly Black schools for kindergarten through twelfth grade students were common throughout the US before the 1970s.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] By 1972, however, desegregation efforts meant that only 25% of Black students were in schools with more than 90% non-White students.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] However, since then, a trend towards re-segregation affected communities across the country: by 2011, 2.9 million African American students were in such overwhelmingly minority schools, including 53% of Black students in school districts that were formerly under desegregation orders.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] As late as 1947, about one third of African Americans over 65 were considered to lack the literacy to read and write their own names.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] By 1969, illiteracy as it had been traditionally defined, had been largely eradicated among younger African Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Between 1995 and 2009, freshmen college enrollment for African Americans increased by 73 percent and only 15 percent for Whites.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Black women are enrolled in college more than any other race and gender group, leading all with 9.7% enrolled according to the 2011 US census.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The average high school graduation rate of Blacks in the United States has steadily increased to 71% in 2013.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Separating this statistic into component parts shows it varies greatly depending upon the state and the school district examined.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] 38% of Black males graduated in the state of New York but in Maine 97% graduated and exceeded the White male graduation rate by 11 percentage points.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In much of the southeastern United States and some parts of the southwestern United States the graduation rate of White males was in fact below 70% such as in Florida where 62% of White males graduated from high school.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Examining specific school districts paints an even more complex picture.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In the Detroit school district, the graduation rate of Black males was 20% but 7% for White males.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In the New York City school district 28% of Black males graduate from high school compared to 57% of White males.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In Newark County 76% of Black males graduated compared to 67% for White males.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Further academic improvement has occurred in 2015.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Roughly 23% of all Blacks have bachelor's degrees.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In 1988, 21% of Whites had obtained a bachelor's degree versus 11% of Blacks.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In 2015, 23% of Blacks had obtained a bachelor's degree versus 36% of Whites.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Foreign born Blacks, 9% of the Black population, made even greater strides.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] They exceed native born Blacks by 10 percentage points.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] College Board, which runs the official college-level advanced placement (AP) programs in American high schools, have has received criticism in recent years that its curricula have focused too much on Euro-centric history.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In 2020, College Board reshaped some curricula among history-based courses to further reflect the African diaspora.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In 2021, College Board announced it would be piloting an AP African American Studies course between 2022 and 2024.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The course officially launched in August 2024.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In June 2023, the Supreme Court ended race-based affirmative action at American colleges and universities.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In response, many of the nation's most prominent historically black colleges and universities (HBCUs) have reported a significant surge in applications and enrollment.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Slightly more than 250,000 African American students in the high school graduating class of 2025 took the Scholastic Aptitude Test (SAT) making up 13% of test takers.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] African American students had an average score of 904 which is lower than the national average of 1,209.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Asian American students had the highest average with 1,229.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] According to a 2025 study, African Americans have the highest average student debt.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] African Americans with bachelor's degrees owe an average of $52,726 in student loans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Nearly 70% of African Americans took out a loan to fund their undergraduate education.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] African American women, in particular, carry the highest average student debt in the nation.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Historically black colleges and universities (HBCUs), which were founded when segregated institutions of higher learning did not admit African Americans, continue to thrive and educate students of all races today.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] There are 107 HBCUs representing three percent of the nation's colleges and universities with the majority established in the Southeast.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] HBCUs have been largely responsible for establishing and expanding the African American middle-class by providing more career opportunities for African Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The economic disparity between the races in the US has marginally improved since the end of slavery.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In 1863, two years prior to emancipation, Black people owned 0.5 percent of the national wealth, while in 2019 it is just over 1.5 percent.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Racial disparity in poverty rates has narrowed since the civil rights era, with the poverty rate among African Americans decreasing from 24.7% in 2004 to 18.8% in 2020, compared to 10.5% for all Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Poverty is associated with higher rates of marital stress and dissolution, physical and mental health problems, disability, cognitive deficits, low educational attainment, and crime.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] African Americans have a long and diverse history of business ownership.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Although the first African American business is unknown, slaves captured from West Africa are believed to have established commercial enterprises as peddlers and skilled craftspeople as far back as the 17th century.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Washington became the most famous proponent of African American businesses.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] DuBois also commended business as a vehicle for African American advancement.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In 2002, African American-owned businesses accounted for 1.2 million of the US's 23 million businesses.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] As of 2011, African American-owned businesses account for approximately two million US businesses.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Black-owned businesses experienced the largest growth in number of businesses among minorities from 2002 to 2011.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Twenty-five percent of Blacks had white-collar occupations (management, professional, and related fields) in 2000, compared with 33.6% of Americans overall.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In 2001, over half of African American households of married couples earned $50,000 or more.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Although in the same year African Americans were over-represented among the nation's poor, this was directly related to the disproportionate percentage of African American families headed by single women; such families are collectively poorer, regardless of ethnicity.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In 2006, the median earnings of African American men was more than Black and non-Black American women overall, and in all educational levels.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] At the same time, among American men, income disparities were significant; the median income of African American men was approximately 76 cents for every dollar of their European American counterparts, although the gap narrowed somewhat with a rise in educational level.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Overall, the median earnings of African American men were 72 cents for every dollar earned of their Asian American counterparts, and $1.17 for every dollar earned by Hispanic men.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] On the other hand, by 2006, among American women with post-secondary education, African American women have made significant advances; the median income of African American women was more than those of their Asian-, European- and Hispanic American counterparts with at least some college education.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The US public sector is the single most important source of employment for African Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] During 2008–2010, 21.2% of all Black workers were public employees, compared with 16.3% of non-Black workers.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Both before and after the onset of the Great Recession, African Americans were 30% more likely than other workers to be employed in the public sector.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The public sector is also a critical source of decent-paying jobs for Black Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] For both men and women, the median wage earned by Black employees is significantly higher in the public sector than in other industries.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In 1999, the median income of African American families was $33,255 compared to $53,356 of European Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In times of economic hardship for the nation, African Americans suffer disproportionately from job loss and underemployment, with the Black underclass being hardest hit.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The phrase "last hired and first fired" is reflected in the Bureau of Labor Statistics unemployment figures.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Nationwide, the October 2008 unemployment rate for African Americans was 11.1%, while the nationwide rate was 6.5%.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In 2007, the average income for African Americans was approximately $34,000, compared to $55,000 for Whites.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] African Americans experience a higher rate of unemployment than the general population.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The income gap between Black and White families is also significant.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In 2005, employed Blacks earned 65% of the wages of Whites, down from 82% in 1975.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] *The New York Times* reported in 2006 that in Queens, New York, the median income among African American families exceeded that of White families, which the newspaper attributed to the growth in the number of two-parent Black families.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] It noted that Queens was the only county with more than 65,000 residents where that was true.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In 2011, it was reported that 72% of Black babies were born to unwed mothers.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The poverty rate among single-parent Black families was 39.5% in 2005, according to Walter E.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Williams, while it was 9.9% among married-couple Black families.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Among White families, the respective rates were 26.4% and 6% in poverty.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Collectively, African Americans are more involved in the American political process than other minority groups in the United States, indicated by the highest level of voter registration and participation in elections among these groups in 2004.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] African Americans also have the highest level of Congressional representation of any minority group in the US.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Homeownership in the US is the strongest indicator of financial stability and the primary asset most Americans use to generate wealth.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] African Americans continue to lag behind other racial groups in homeownership.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In the first quarter of 2021, 45.1% of African Americans owned their homes, compared to 65.3% of all Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The African American homeownership rate has remained relatively flat since the 1970s despite an increase in anti-discrimination housing laws and protections.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The African American homeownership rate peaked in 2004 at 49.7%.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The average White high school drop-out still has a slightly better chance of owning a home than the average African American college graduate usually due to unfavorable debt-to-income ratios or credit scores among most African American college graduates.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Since 2000, fast-growing housing costs in most cities have made it even more difficult for the US African American homeownership rate to significantly grow and reach over 50% for the first time in history.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] From 2000 to 2022, the median home price in the US grew 160%, outpacing average annual household income growth in that same period, which only grew about 30%.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] South Carolina is the state with the most African American homeownership, with about 55% of African Americans owning their own homes.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Black people, who make up 12% of the total U.S. population, make up 32% of all people experiencing homelessness, according to the data.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Since the mid 20th century, a large majority of African Americans support the Democratic Party.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In the 2024 Presidential election, 86% of African American voters supported Democrat Kamala Harris, while 13% supported Republican Donald Trump.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Although there is an African American lobby in foreign policy, it has not had the impact that African American organizations have had in domestic policy.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Many African Americans were excluded from electoral politics in the decades following the end of Reconstruction.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The African American trend of voting for Democrats can be traced back to the 1930s during the Great Depression, when Franklin D.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Roosevelt's New Deal program provided economic relief to African Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Roosevelt's New Deal coalition turned the Democratic Party into an organization of the working class and their liberal allies, regardless of region.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The African American vote became even more solidly Democratic when Democratic presidents John F.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Johnson pushed for civil rights legislation during the 1960s.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In 1960, nearly a third of African Americans voted for Republican Richard Nixon.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Conservatism has been growing among African Americans, particularly since the 2020 Presidential election.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In the 2024 election, Trump secured a slightly larger share of the African American vote compared to his 2020 performance.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] "Lift Every Voice and Sing" is often referred to as the Black national anthem in the United States.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In 1919, the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) had dubbed it the "Negro national anthem" for its power in voicing a cry for liberation and affirmation for African-American people.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The majority of African Americans are Protestant, many of whom follow the historically Black churches.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The term Black church refers to churches which minister to predominantly African American congregations.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Black congregations were first established by freed slaves at the end of the 17th century, and later when slavery was abolished more African Americans were allowed to create a unique form of Christianity that was culturally influenced by African spiritual traditions.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] According to a 2007 survey, more than half of the African American population are part of the historically Black churches.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The largest Protestant denomination among African Americans is the Baptists, distributed mainly in four denominations, the largest being the National Baptist Convention, USA and the National Baptist Convention of America.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The second-largest is the Methodists, the largest organizations of which are the African Methodist Episcopal Church and the African Methodist Episcopal Zion Church.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Pentecostals are distributed among several different religious bodies, with the Church of God in Christ as the largest among them by far.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] About 16% of African American Christians are members of White Protestant communions; these denominations (which include the United Church of Christ) mostly have a 2–3% African American membership.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] There are also large numbers of Catholics, constituting 5% of the African American population.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Of the total number of Jehovah's Witnesses, 22% are Black.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Historically, between 15 and 30% of enslaved Africans brought to the Americas were Muslims, but most of these Africans were converted to Christianity during the era of American slavery.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Prominent members included activist Malcolm X and boxer Muhammad Ali.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Malcolm X is considered the first person to start the movement among African Americans towards mainstream Islam, after he left the Nation and made the pilgrimage to Mecca.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In 1975, Warith Deen Mohammed, the son of Elijah Muhammad took control of the Nation after his father's death and guided the majority of its members to orthodox Islam.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] African American Muslims constitute 20% of the total US Muslim population, the majority are Sunni or orthodox Muslims, some of these identify under the community of W.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The Nation of Islam led by Louis Farrakhan has a membership ranging from 20,000 to 50,000 members.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] There is also a small but growing group of African American Jews, making up less than 0.5% of African Americans or about 2% of the Jewish population in the United States.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The majority of African-American Jews are Ashkenazi, while smaller numbers identify as Sephardi, Mizrahi, or other.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Many African-American Jews are affiliated with denominations such as the Reform, Conservative, Reconstructionist, or Orthodox branches of Judaism, but the majority identify as "Jews of no religion", commonly known as secular Jews.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] A significant number of people who identify themselves as "Black Jews" are affiliated with syncretic religious groups, largely the Black Hebrew Israelites, whose beliefs include the claim that African Americans are descended from the Biblical Israelites.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Jews of all races typically do not accept Black Hebrew Israelites as Jews, in part because they are usually not Jewish according to Jewish law, and in part because these groups are sometimes associated with antisemitism.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] African-American Jews have criticized the Black Hebrew Israelites, regarding the movement as primarily composed of Black non-Jews who have appropriated Black-Jewish identity.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In the 2010s, confirmed atheists were less than one half of one percent, similar to numbers for Hispanics.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In 2025, a Pew Research Center study found that, among Black Americans, Christian affiliation has declined in recent years.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The share of Black adults identifying as Christian fell from 85% in 2007 to 79% in 2014 and 73% in 2021, mirroring a broader decline in Christianity in the United States.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] However, Black adults remain more likely than U.S. adults overall to identify as Christian (73% vs.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] By comparison, about half or fewer adults in other racial or ethnic groups report that religion is very important or that they pray daily, and even smaller shares attend services monthly.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Religiosity among Black Americans also varies by age.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] 39% of Black adults aged 65 and older describe themselves as very religious, compared with 21% of those under 30.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] This age pattern is similar to that observed among White and Hispanic Americans, although Black adults of all ages are more likely than other groups to describe themselves as very religious.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] According to a Gallup survey, 4.6% of Black or African Americans self-identified as LGBT in 2016, while the total portion of American adults in all ethnic groups identifying as LGBT was 4.1% in 2016.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] African American women are more likely than African American men to openly identify as LGBT.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The life expectancy for Black men in 2008 was 70.8 years.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Life expectancy for Black women was 77.5 years in 2008.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In 1900, when information on Black life expectancy started being collated, a Black man could expect to live to 32.5 years and a Black woman 33.5 years.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In 1900, White men lived an average of 46.3 years and White women lived an average of 48.3 years.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] African American life expectancy at birth is persistently five to seven years lower than European Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Black men have shorter lifespans than any other group in the US besides Native American men.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Black people have higher rates of obesity, diabetes, and hypertension than the US average.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] For adult Black men, the rate of obesity was 31.6% in 2010.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] For adult Black women, the rate of obesity was 41.2% in 2010.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] African Americans have higher rates of mortality than any other racial or ethnic group for eight of the top ten causes of death.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In 2013, among men, Black men had the highest rate of getting cancer, followed by White, Hispanic, Asian/Pacific Islander (A/PI), and American Indian/Alaska Native (AI/AN) men.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Among women, White women had the highest rate of getting cancer, followed by Black, Hispanic, Asian/Pacific Islander, and American Indian/Alaska Native women.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] African Americans also have higher prevalence and incidence of Alzheimer's disease compared to the overall average.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Black women lead the nation in abortions.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] According to a 2022 report, Black women made up 40% of abortions despite making up 13% of the U.S. woman population.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] African Americans are more likely than White Americans to die due to health-related problems developed by alcoholism.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Alcohol abuse is the main contributor to the top three causes of death among African Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In December 2020, African Americans were less likely to be vaccinated against COVID-19 due to mistrust in the US medical system.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] From 2021 to 2022, there was an increase in African Americans who became vaccinated.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Still, in 2022, COVID-19 complications became the third leading cause of death for African Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Violence is a major problem within the African American community.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] A report from the US Department of Justice states "In 2005, homicide victimization rates for Blacks were more than six times as high as the rates for Whites".
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The report also found that "94% of Black victims were killed by Blacks." Of the nearly 20,000 recorded US homicides in 2022, African Americans made up the majority of offenders and victims despite making up less than 15% of the population.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In 2024, all of the five most dangerous US cities have a significant Black population and highly concerning Black-on-Black violent crime rate.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Black males age 15–44 are the only race/sex category for which homicide is a top-five cause of death.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Black women are three times more likely to be killed by an intimate partner than White women.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Black children are more than three times as likely to die due to parental abuse and neglect than White children.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, African Americans have higher rates of sexually transmitted infections (STIs) compared to Whites, with five times the rates of syphilis and chlamydia, and 7.5 times the rate of gonorrhea.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The disproportionately high incidence of HIV/AIDS among African Americans has been attributed to homophobic influences, lack of condom usage, and lack of proper healthcare.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The prevalence of HIV/AIDS among Black men is seven times higher than the prevalence for White men, and Black men are more than nine times as likely to die from HIV/AIDS-related illness than White men.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The prevalence of HIV/AIDS among Black women is 20 times higher than White women, and Black women are more than 15 times as likely to die from HIV/AIDS-related illness than White women.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] African Americans have several barriers for accessing mental health services.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Counseling has been frowned upon and distant in utility and proximity to many people in the African American community.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In 2004, a qualitative research study explored the disconnect with African Americans and mental health.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The study was conducted as a semi-structured discussion which allowed the focus group to express their opinions and life experiences.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] The results revealed a couple key variables that create barriers for many African American communities to seek mental health services such as the stigma, lack of four important necessities; trust, affordability, cultural understanding and impersonal services.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Historically, many African American communities did not seek counseling because religion was a part of the family values.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] African Americans who have a faith background are more likely to seek prayer as a coping mechanism for mental issues rather than seeking professional mental health services.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In 2015 a study concluded, African Americans with high value in religion are less likely to utilize mental health services compared to those who have low value in religion.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In the United States, counseling approaches are based on the experience of White Americans and do not fit within the African American culture.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] African American families tend to resolve concerns within the family, and it is viewed by the family as a strength.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] On the other hand, when African Americans seek counseling, they face a social backlash and are criticized.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] They may be labeled "crazy", viewed as weak, and their pride is diminished.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Because of this, many African Americans instead seek mentorship within communities they trust.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Terminology is another barrier in relation to African Americans and mental health.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] There is more stigma on the term *psychotherapy* versus counseling.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In one study, psychotherapy is associated with mental illness whereas counseling approaches problem-solving, guidance and help.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] More African Americans seek assistance when it is called counseling and not psychotherapy because it is more welcoming within the culture and community.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Counselors are encouraged to be aware of such barriers for the well-being of African American clients.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] Without cultural competency training in health care, many African Americans go unheard and misunderstood.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] In 2021, African Americans had the third highest suicide rate trailing American Indians/Alaska Natives and White Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] However, African Americans had the second highest increase of its suicide rate from 2011 to 2021, growing 58%.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p02] As of 2024, suicide is the second leading cause of death among African-Americans between the ages of 15 and 24, with Black men being four times more likely to kill themselves than Black women.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Recent studies of African Americans using genetic testing have found ancestry to vary by region and sex of ancestors.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] These studies found that on average, African Americans have 73.2–82.1% Sub-Saharan African, 16.7–24% European, and 0.8–1.2% Native American genetic ancestry, with large variation between individuals.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Commercial testing services have reported similar variation, with ranges from 0.6 to 2 percent Native American, 19 to 29 percent European, and 65 to 80 percent Sub-Saharan African ancestry.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] According to a genome-wide study by Bryc et al.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] (2009), the mixed ancestry of African Americans in varying ratios came about as the result of sexual contact between West/Central Africans (more frequently females) and Europeans (more frequently males).
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] This can be understood as being the result of enslaved African American females being raped by White males.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Consequently, the 365 African Americans in their sample have a genome-wide average of 78.1% West African ancestry and 18.5% European ancestry, with large variation among individuals (ranging from 99% to 1% West African ancestry).
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] The West African ancestral component in African Americans is most similar to that in present-day speakers from the non-Bantu branches of the Niger-Congo family.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] (2014) observed that around 50% of the overall ancestry of African Americans traces comes from a population similar to the Niger-Congo-speaking Yoruba of southern Nigeria and southern Benin, reflecting the centrality of this West African region in the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] The next most frequent ancestral component found among African Americans was derived from Great Britain, in keeping with historical records.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] It constitutes a little over 10% of their overall ancestry and is most similar to the Northwest European ancestral component also carried by Barbadians.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] (2009) found a similar proportion of Yoruba-like ancestry in their African American samples, with a minority also drawn from Mandenka and Bantu populations.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Additionally, the researchers observed an average European ancestry of 21.9%, again with significant variation between individuals.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] (2009) note that populations from other parts of the continent may also constitute adequate proxies for the ancestors of some African American individuals; namely, ancestral populations from Guinea Bissau, Senegal and Sierra Leone in West Africa and Angola in Southern Africa.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] An individual African American person can have over fifteen African ethnic groups in their genetic makeup alone due to the slave trade covering such vast areas.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Altogether, genetic studies suggest that African Americans are a genetically diverse people.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] According to DNA analysis led in 2006 by Penn State geneticist Mark D.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] According to Shriver, around five percent of African Americans also have at least 12.5% Native American ancestry (equivalent to one Native American great-grandparent and their forebears).
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Research suggests that Native American ancestry among people who identify as African American is a result of relationships that occurred soon after slave ships arrived in the American colonies, and European ancestry is of more recent origin, often from the decades before the Civil War.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Africans bearing the E-V38 (E1b1a) likely traversed across the Sahara, from east to west, approximately 19,000 years ago.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] E-M2 (E1b1a1) likely originated in West Africa or Central Africa.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] According to a Y-DNA study by Sims et al.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] (2007), the majority (≈60%) of African Americans belong to various subclades of the E-M2 (E1b1a1, formerly E3a) paternal haplogroup.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] This is the most common genetic paternal lineage found today among West/Central African males and is also a signature of the historical Bantu migrations.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] The next most frequent Y-DNA haplogroup observed among African Americans is the R1b clade, which around 15% of African Americans carry.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] This lineage is most common today among Northwestern European males.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] The remaining African Americans mainly belong to the paternal haplogroup I (≈7%), which is also frequent in Northwestern Europe.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] According to an mtDNA study by Salas et al.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] (2005), the maternal lineages of African Americans are most similar to haplogroups that are today especially common in West Africa (>55%), followed closely by West-Central Africa and Southwestern Africa (<41%).
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] The characteristic West African haplogroups L1b, L2b,c,d, and L3b,d and West-Central African haplogroups L1c and L3e in particular occur at high frequencies among African Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] As with the paternal DNA of African Americans, contributions from other parts of the continent to their maternal gene pool are insignificant.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Formal political, economic and social discrimination against minorities has been present throughout American history.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Saito, Associate Professor of Sociology and American Studies & Ethnicity at the University of Southern California, writes, "Political rights have been circumscribed by race, class and gender since the founding of the United States, when the right to vote was restricted to White men of property.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Those who economically gained the most from slavery were the planter class, owners of large-scale plantations where large numbers of enslaved Africans were held captive and forced to produce crops to create wealth for a White elite.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Although they have gained a greater degree of social equality since the civil rights movement, African Americans have remained stagnant economically, which has hindered their ability to break into the middle class and beyond.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] As of 2020, the racial wealth gap between Whites and Blacks remains as large as it was in 1968, with the typical net worth of a White household equivalent to that of 11.5 Black households.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Despite this, African Americans have increased employment rates and gained representation in the highest levels of American government in the post–civil rights era.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] However, widespread racism remains an issue that continues to undermine the development of social status.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Economically, of all the racially Black ethnic groups on the globe, African Americans are the wealthiest and most successful, with one in every fifty African American families being millionaires.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] This equates in 2023 to approximately 1.79 million African American millionaires in the United States, which is more than the number of millionaires in any racially Black country, and many other countries, around the world.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] In the US, which has the largest per-capita prison population in the world, African Americans are overrepresented as the second-largest population of prison inmates (38%) in 2023, coming second to Whites, who made up 57% of the prison population.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] According to the National Registry of Exonerations, Blacks are roughly 7.5 times more likely to be wrongfully convicted of murder in the US than Whites.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] In 2012, the New York City Police Department detained people more than 500,000 times under the city's stop-and-frisk law.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Of the total detained, 55% were African-Americans, while Black people made up 20% of the city's population.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] African American males are more likely to be killed by police when compared to other races.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] This is one of the factors that led to the creation of the Black Lives Matter movement in 2013.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] According to *The Guardian*, "The specter of Karen persisted as Black Lives Matter protests and civil unrest spread around the country following Floyd's murder and reckonings with racism began to roil institutions, toppling careers as well as statues".
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] In the aftermath of the peak Black Lives Matter protests and widespread police reform efforts in the early 2020s, crime rates surged across the nation, especially in predominantly Black neighborhoods.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Many cities experienced near-record or record levels of violence and other criminal activity.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] As a result, numerous municipalities scaled back police reform initiatives and increased funding for law enforcement.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] After over 50 years, marriage rates for all Americans began to decline while divorce rates and out-of-wedlock births have climbed.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] These changes have been greatest among African Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] After more than 70 years of racial parity Black marriage rates began to fall behind Whites.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Single-parent households have become most common, and according to US census figures released in January 2010, only 38% of Black children lived with both their parents.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] In 2021, statistics show that over 80% marriages in the African American ethnic group marry within their ethnic group.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Black children are overrepresented in the U.S. foster care system.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] In 2017, Black American children made up 14% of the children population but 22% of those in the foster care system.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Black American children are more than twice as likely to be placed in foster care than White American children.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] The first ever anti-miscegenation law was passed by the Maryland General Assembly in 1691, criminalizing interracial marriage.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] In a speech in Charleston, Illinois in 1858, Abraham Lincoln stated, "I am not, nor ever have been in favor of making voters or jurors of negroes, nor of qualifying them to hold office, nor to intermarry with white people".
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] By the late 1800s, 38 US states had anti-miscegenation statutes.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] By 1924, the ban on interracial marriage was still in force in 29 states.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] While interracial marriage had been legal in California since 1948, in 1957 actor Sammy Davis Jr. faced a backlash for his involvement with White actress Kim Novak.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Harry Cohn, the president of Columbia Pictures, with whom Novak was under contract, gave in to his concerns that a racist backlash against the relationship could hurt the studio.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Davis briefly married Black dancer Loray White in 1958 to protect himself from mob violence.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Inebriated at the wedding ceremony, Davis despairingly said to his best friend, Arthur Silber Jr., "Why won't they let me live my life?" The couple never lived together, and commenced divorce proceedings in September 1958.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] In 1967 the law was ruled unconstitutional (via the 14th Amendment adopted in 1868) by the US Supreme Court in *Loving v.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] In 2008, Democrats overwhelmingly voted 70% against California Proposition 8, African Americans voted 58% in favor of it while 42% voted against Proposition 8.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] On May 9, 2012, Barack Obama, the first Black president, became the first US president to support same-sex marriage.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Since Obama's endorsement there has been a rapid growth in support for same-sex marriage among African Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] As of 2012, 59% of African Americans support same-sex marriage, which is higher than support among the national average (53%) and White Americans (50%).
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Polls in North Carolina, Pennsylvania, Missouri, Maryland, Ohio, Florida, and Nevada have also shown an increase in support for same sex marriage among African Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] On November 6, 2012, Maryland, Maine, and Washington all voted for approve of same-sex marriage, along with Minnesota rejecting a constitutional amendment banning same-sex marriage.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Exit polls in Maryland show about 50% of African Americans voted for same-sex marriage, showing a vast evolution among African Americans on the issue and was crucial in helping pass same-sex marriage in Maryland.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Black Americans hold far more conservative opinions on abortion, extramarital sex, and raising children out of wedlock than Democrats as a whole.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] On financial issues, however, African Americans are in line with Democrats, generally supporting a more progressive tax structure to provide more government spending on social services.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] African Americans have fought in every war in the history of the United States.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] The gains made by African Americans in the civil rights movement and in the Black Power movement not only obtained certain rights for African Americans but changed American society in far-reaching and fundamentally important ways.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Prior to the 1950s, Black Americans in the South were subject to de jure discrimination, or Jim Crow laws.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] They were often the victims of extreme cruelty and violence, sometimes resulting in deaths: by the post World War II era, African Americans became increasingly discontented with their long-standing inequality.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] The civil rights movement marked an enormous change in American social, political, economic and civic life.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Over time, it has changed in fundamental ways the manner in which Blacks and Whites interact with and relate to one another.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Some activists and academics contend that American news media coverage of African American news, concerns, or dilemmas is inadequate, or that the news media present distorted images of African Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Johnson founded Black Entertainment Television (BET), a network that targets young African Americans and urban audiences in the United States.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Over the years, the network has aired such programming as rap and R&B music videos, urban-oriented movies and television series, and some public affairs programs.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] On Sunday mornings, BET would broadcast Christian programming; the network would also broadcast non-affiliated Christian programs during the early morning hours daily.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] According to Viacom, BET is now a global network that reaches households in the United States, Caribbean, Canada, and the United Kingdom.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] The network has gone on to spawn several spin-off channels, including BET Her (originally launched as *BET on Jazz*).
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Another network targeting African Americans is TV One.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] TV One is owned by Urban One, founded and controlled by Catherine Hughes.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Urban One is one of the nation's largest radio broadcasting companies and the largest African American-owned radio broadcasting company in the United States.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] In June 2009, NBC News launched a new website named TheGrio.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] It is the first African American video news site that focuses on underrepresented stories in existing national news.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] From their earliest presence in North America, African Americans have significantly contributed literature, art, agricultural skills, cuisine, clothing styles, music, language, and social and technological innovation to American culture.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] The cultivation and use of many agricultural products in the United States, such as yams, peanuts, rice, okra, sorghum, grits, watermelon, indigo dyes, and cotton, can be traced to West African and African American influences.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Notable examples include George Washington Carver, who created nearly 500 products from peanuts, sweet potatoes, and pecans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Soul food is a variety of cuisine popular among African Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] It is closely related to the cuisine of the Southern United States.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] The descriptive terminology may have originated in the mid-1960s, when *soul* was a common definer used to describe African American culture (for example, soul music).
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] African Americans were the first peoples in the United States to make fried chicken, along with Scottish immigrants to the South.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Although the Scottish had been frying chicken before they emigrated, they lacked the spices and flavor that African Americans had used when preparing the meal.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] The Scottish American settlers therefore adopted the African American method of seasoning chicken.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] However, fried chicken was generally a rare meal in the African American community and was usually reserved for special events or celebrations.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] African-American English is a variety (dialect, ethnolect, and sociolect) of American English, commonly spoken by urban working-class and largely bi-dialectal middle-class African Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] It shares parts of its grammar and phonology with the Southern American English dialect.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] African American English differs from Standard American English (SAE) in certain pronunciation characteristics, tense usage, and grammatical structures, which were derived from West African languages (particularly those belonging to the Niger–Congo family).
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Virtually all habitual speakers of African American English can understand and communicate in Standard American English.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] As with all linguistic forms, AAVE's usage is influenced by various factors, including geographical, educational and socioeconomic background, as well as formality of setting.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Additionally, there are many literary uses of this variety of English, particularly in African American literature.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Other languages are spoken by specific sub-communities.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] The Gullah language is an English-based creole language spoken mostly in the coastal regions of South Carolina and Georgia by the Gullah; an off-shoot of this is Afro-Seminole Creole spoken by Black Seminoles mostly now in Mexico and Brackettville, Texas.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Louisiana Creole is a French-based creole and spoken mostly in Louisiana.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] African-American names are part of the cultural traditions of African Americans, most of these cultural names having no connection to Africa but strictly an African American cultural practice that developed in the United States during enslavement.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] This new evidence became apparent by census records which show African Americans and White Americans, though they spoke the same language, chose to use different names even during times of enslavement, which is where and when the development of African American cultural names began.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Prior to this newer information, it was only thought that before the 1950s, and 1960s, most African-American names closely resembled those used within European-American culture.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Babies of that era were generally given a few common names, with children using nicknames to distinguish the various people with the same name.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] With the rise of 1960s civil rights movement, there was a dramatic increase in names of various origins.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] By the 1970s, and 1980s, it had become common among African Americans to invent new names for themselves, although many of these invented names took elements from popular existing names.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Prefixes such as La/Le, Da/De, Ra/Re and Ja/Je, and suffixes like -ique/iqua, -isha and -aun/-awn are common, as are inventive spellings for common names.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] The book *Baby Names Now: From Classic to Cool—The Very Last Word on First Names* places the origins of "La" names in African-American culture in New Orleans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Even with the rise of inventive names, it is still common for African Americans to use biblical, historical, or traditional European names.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Daniel, Christopher, Michael, David, James, Joseph, and Matthew were thus among the most frequent names for African-American boys in 2013.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] The name LaKeisha is typically considered American in origin but has elements that were drawn from both French and West/Central African roots.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Names such as LaTanisha, JaMarcus, DeAndre, and Shaniqua were created in the same way.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Punctuation marks are seen more often within African American names than other American names, such as the names Mo'nique and D'Andre.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] African American music is one of the most pervasive African American cultural influences in the United States today and is among the most dominant in mainstream popular music.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Hip-hop, R&B, funk, rock and roll, soul, blues, and other contemporary American musical forms originated in Black communities and evolved from other Black forms of music, including blues, doo-wop, barbershop, ragtime, bluegrass, jazz, and gospel music.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] African American-derived musical forms have also influenced and been incorporated into virtually every other popular music genre in the world, including country and techno.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] African Americans have also had an important role in American dance.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Jones, a prominent modern choreographer and dancer, has included historical African American themes in his work, particularly in the piece "Last Supper at Uncle Tom's Cabin/The Promised Land".
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Likewise, Alvin Ailey's artistic work, including his "Revelations" based on his experience growing up as an African American in the South during the 1930s, has had a significant influence on modern dance.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Another form of dance, stepping, is an African American tradition whose performance and competition has been formalized through the traditionally Black fraternities and sororities at universities.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Discussions of race and sports in the United States, where the two subjects have always been intertwined in American history, have focused to a great extent on African Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Depending on the type of sport and performance level, African Americans are reported to be over- or under-represented.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] African Americans compose the highest percentage of the minority groups active at the professional level, but are among those who show the lowest participation overall.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] And though the list of African Americans in professional sports remains high, it only represents a small fraction of aspiring black athletes.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Many African American authors have written stories, poems, and essays influenced by their experiences as African Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] African American literature is a major genre in American literature.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Famous examples include Langston Hughes, James Baldwin, Richard Wright, Zora Neale Hurston, Ralph Ellison, Nobel Prize winner Toni Morrison, and Maya Angelou.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] African American inventors have created many widely used devices in the world and have contributed to international innovation.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Norbert Rillieux created the technique for converting sugar cane juice into white sugar crystals.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Moreover, Rillieux left Louisiana in 1854 and went to France, where he spent ten years working with the Champollions deciphering Egyptian hieroglyphics from the Rosetta Stone.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Most slave inventors were nameless, such as the slave owned by the Confederate President Jefferson Davis who designed the ship propeller used by the Confederate navy.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] By 1913, over 1,000 inventions were patented by Black Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Among the most notable inventors were Jan Matzeliger, who developed the first machine to mass-produce shoes, and Elijah McCoy, who invented automatic lubrication devices for steam engines.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Granville Woods had 35 patents to improve electric railway systems, including the first system to allow moving trains to communicate.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Morgan developed the first automatic traffic signal and gas mask.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Lewis Howard Latimer invented an improvement for the incandescent light bulb.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] More recent inventors include Frederick McKinley Jones, who invented the movable refrigeration unit for food transport in trucks and trains.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Lloyd Quarterman worked with six other Black scientists on the creation of the atomic bomb (code named the Manhattan Project) and helped develop the first nuclear reactor.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] As part of the preservation of their culture, African Americans have continuously launched their own publications and publishing houses, such as Robert Sengstacke Abbott, founder of the Chicago Defender newspaper, and Carter G.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Woodson, the founder of Black History Month who spent over thirty years documenting and publishing African American history in journals and books.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] The Johnson Publishing Company, founded by John H.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Johnson in 1942, is a National Historic Landmark.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] The term *African American* was popularized by Jesse Jackson in the 1980s, although there are recorded uses from the 18th and 19th centuries, for example, in post-emancipation holidays and conferences.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Earlier terms also used to describe Americans of African ancestry referred more to skin color than to ancestry.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Other terms (such as *colored*, *person of color*, or *negro*) were included in the wording of various laws and legal decisions which some thought were being used as tools of White supremacy and oppression.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] A 16-page pamphlet entitled "A Sermon on the Capture of Lord Cornwallis" is notable for the attribution of its authorship to "An *African American*".
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Published in 1782, the book's use of this phrase predates any other yet identified by more than 50 years.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] In the 1980s, the term *African American* was advanced to give descendants of American slaves, and other American Blacks who lived through the slavery era, a heritage and a cultural base.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] The term was popularized in Black communities around the country via word of mouth and ultimately received mainstream use after Jesse Jackson's use in 1988.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Subsequently, major media outlets adopted it.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Surveys in the 1990s and the first decade of the 21st century showed that the majority of Black Americans had no preference for *African American* versus *Black American*, although they had a slight preference for the latter in personal settings and the former in more formal settings.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] By 2021, according to polling from Gallup, 58% of Black Americans expressed no preference for what their group should be called, with 17% each preferring *Black* and *African-American*.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] In 2023, the government released a new more detailed breakdown due to the rise in racially Black immigration into the US, listing African American as a compound termed ethnicity, distinguished from other racially Black ethnicities such as Nigerian, Jamaican etc.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] The term *African American* embraces pan-Africanism as earlier enunciated by prominent African thinkers such as Marcus Garvey, W.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] The term *Afro-Usonian*, and variations of such, are more rarely used.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] In preparation for the 2010 US census, a marketing and outreach plan called *2010 Census Integrated Communications Campaign Plan* (ICC) recognized and defined African Americans as Black people born in the United States.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] From the ICC perspective, African Americans are one of three groups of Black people in the United States: African Americans, Black Africans, and Afro-Caribbeans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] The ICC plan was to reach the three groups by acknowledging that each group has its own sense of community that is based on geography and ethnicity.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] The best way to market the census process toward any of the three groups is to reach them through their own unique communication channels and not treat the entire Black population of the US as though they are all African Americans with a single ethnic and geographical background.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Historically, "race mixing" between Black and White people was taboo in the United States.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] So-called anti-miscegenation laws, barring Blacks and Whites from marrying or having sex, were established in colonial America as early as 1691, and endured in many Southern states until the Supreme Court ruled them unconstitutional in *Loving v.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] The taboo among American Whites surrounding White-Black relations is a historical consequence of the oppression and racial segregation of African Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Harvard University historian Henry Louis Gates Jr. wrote in 2009 that "African Americans...are a racially mixed or mulatto people—deeply and overwhelmingly so".
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] After the Emancipation Proclamation, Chinese American men married African American women in high proportions to their total marriage numbers due to few Chinese American women being in the United States.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] African slaves and their descendants have also had a history of cultural exchange and intermarriage with Native Americans, although they did not necessarily retain social, cultural or linguistic ties to Native peoples.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] There are also increasing intermarriages and offspring between non-Hispanic Blacks and Hispanics of any race, especially between Puerto Ricans and African Americans.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Racially mixed marriages have become increasingly accepted in the United States since the civil rights movement.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] A Gallup poll conducted in 2013 found that 84% of Whites and 96% of Blacks approved of interracial marriage, and 87% overall.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Black men are more than twice as likely to date and marry interracially than Black women.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] At the end of World War II, some African American military men stationed in Asia and Europe impregnated local non-Black women, resulting in the birth of thousands of mixed-race children called "Brown Babies".
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Some of these families later immigrated to the United States.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] However, some mixed-race children, especially in Japan, were placed in orphanages due to social stigmas associated with half-Black fatherless children in the 1950s.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Author Debra Dickerson has argued that the term *Black* should refer strictly to the descendants of Africans who were brought to America as slaves, and not to the sons and daughters of Black immigrants who lack that ancestry.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Thus, under her definition, President Barack Obama, who is the son of a Kenyan, is not Black.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] "Lumping us all together", Dickerson wrote, "erases the significance of slavery and continuing racism while giving the appearance of progress." Similar comments have been made concerning Kamala Harris, the daughter of a Jamaican immigrant, who was elected vice president in 2020.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] The American Descendants of Slavery (ADOS) movement coalesces around this view, arguing that Black descendants of American slavery deserve a separate ethnic category that distinguishes them from other Black groups in the United States.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Their terminology has gained popularity in some circles, but others have criticized the movement for a perceived bias against (especially poor and Black) immigrants, and for its often inflammatory rhetoric.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Politicians such as Obama and Harris have received especially pointed criticism from the movement, as neither are ADOS and have spoken out at times against policies specific to them.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Most notably, Malcolm X and Kwame Ture expressed similar views that African Americans are Africans who "happen to be in America", and should not claim or identify as being American if they are fighting for Black (New Afrikan) liberation.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Historically, this is due to the enslavement of Africans during the transatlantic slave trade, ongoing anti-Black violence, and structural racism in countries like the United States.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Before the independence of the Thirteen Colonies until the abolition of slavery in 1865, an African American slave was commonly known as a *negro*.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] *Free negro* was the legal status in the territory of an African American person who was not enslaved.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] The term was used until the second quarter of the 20th century, when it was considered outmoded – although it was retained in the name of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) – and generally gave way again to the exclusive use of *negro*.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] By the 1940s, the term was commonly capitalized (*Negro*); but by the mid-1960s, it was considered disparaging.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] By the end of the 20th century, *negro* had come to be considered inappropriate and was rarely used and perceived as a pejorative.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] The term is rarely used by younger Black people, but remained in use by many older African Americans who had grown up with the term, particularly in the Southern US.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] The term remains in use in some contexts, such as the United Negro College Fund, an American philanthropic organization.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] There are many other deliberately insulting terms, many of which were in common use (e.g., *nigger*), but had become unacceptable in normal discourse before the end of the 20th century.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] One exception is the use, among the Black community, of the slur *nigger* rendered as *nigga*, representing the pronunciation of the word in African American English.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] This usage has been popularized by American rap and hip-hop music cultures and is used as part of an in-group lexicon and speech.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] It is not necessarily derogatory and, when used among Black people, the word is often used to mean "homie" or "friend".
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] Acceptance of intra-group usage of the word *nigga* is still debated, although it has established a foothold among younger generations.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/african-american-p03] The NAACP denounces the use of both *nigga* and *nigger*.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/agropelter] The **Agropelter** (given the mock-taxonomic designation *Anthrocephalus craniofractens*) is a mythical fearsome critter said to inhabit hollow trees of the conifer woods from Maine to Oregon.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/agropelter] From this vantage point, the creature would await an unwary person and hurl wooden splinters and branches at the intruder.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/agropelter] Some have described the creature as being so quick that it has never been seen.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/agropelter] The agropelter subsists on woodpeckers, hoot owls, high-holes, and dozy (rotten) wood.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/agropelter] Its pups are born on February 29 and always arrive in odd numbers.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/agropelter] They are blamed for the disappearance of people in northern forests.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/agropelter] When loggers died from branches falling on their heads, the agropelter was blamed for throwing the heavy branches.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/agropelter] In one account, an agropelter kidnapped a pioneer surveyor and fed him raw fish until he escaped.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/agropelter] Torrey Peters' story Stag Dance in the book of the same name features an agropelter.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] The beginning of the decline of native speakers of Alaska Native languages can be traced back to the colonization of Alaska by the United States of America.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] At this time, many native people were separated from their traditional lifestyles and subsequently their native languages.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Due to a new-found language barrier, new generations of Alaska Natives could not communicate with their elders and therefore could not inherit all of the traditional stories.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] New technology has also reinvigorated the art through various webcasts and other online mediums; however the amount of native speakers is still declining.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Despite the rapid decline in spoken Alaska Native languages, the tradition of storytelling in Alaska remains alive.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Storytellers pass down myths, legends, and traditions within their tribes.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] They use inflection in their voices, hand gestures and movement to tell the stories.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] When performing, tellers wear traditional clothing and other garments.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] They also bring objects such as carvings, rugs, and pottery to represent the teller's tribe.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Tellers do not censor the stories; the children hear exactly the same stories older generations have listened to.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Short tales are often told by anyone who has memorized the story.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] The stories are retold to the youth to promote proper behavior in their culture; storytellers learn the stories through repeated tellings.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Tellers are allowed to change and add to a short story and sometimes seek suggestions from fellow storytellers on what they can correct or add to their tellings.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Tribes are more strict with traditional tales, which are usually told by the Elders.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Storytellers learn long, complicated stories by being apprenticed with Elders.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] The tellers are required to recite the stories accurately before delivering it to an audience.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] The stories do not have to be told the same way, but each retelling must include all the elements.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Before telling a story, the storyteller begins with a formatted introduction.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] The introduction includes the storyteller’s English and Native names, hometown, family background, and how they learned the story.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] If the story does not belong to them, they must also honor the owner or credit the source.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Part of storytelling is the interaction between the storyteller and the audience.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] The audience and their response to the story influence how the story is told.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] The teller reads the audience’s body language and determines how to continue with the story; depending on the response, tellers may choose to speed up, slow down, or finish a story.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Storytellers also encourage audience participation to keep the listeners interested in the story.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Storytellers do not tell the audience the moral or point of the story; it is up to them to figure it out on their own.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] During a telling, the audience generates mental images of what is happening and they create different versions of the story.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] In the end, each audience member leaves the performance with his or her own understanding of the story.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Nature is a huge part of the lives of Alaska Natives and it has an influence on their story-telling.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Alaska Natives tell stories where nature plays a main role.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Nature is a great influence in the story-telling because native people have respect for it.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] The seasons play a large role in Alaska Native storytelling.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] When the events in a story involve the seasons, the relating elements are used.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] There are bodies of water, forests, mountains and tundra mentioned in a story when the events in a story are based on seasons other than winter.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] The spring, summer and fall play a smaller part in Native stories, but when these seasons are used, the story usually involves people hiking in the wild.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] When the events are based in a season other than the winter, aspects of an Alaskan summer, like longer days and sunshine, are involved.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] The majority of stories are set in winter.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Winter is usually described as cruel and harsh, with extremely cold temperatures, heavy snowfall, and biting winds.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] When the story is centered during winter, the story-tellers will use the forces in nature such as the snow, wind storms, blizzards, and the ice.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] A massive part of Alaska’s region is covered by glaciers and it influences the storytelling.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Plants do not have as vital of a part in the storytelling as seasons have.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Some plants and trees are described in the stories that are found in Alaska’s wilds: birch (regular and dwarf), spruce, wild roses, as well as different kinds of bushes.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] The ice pack and the mountains are often described in story-telling because a large part of Alaska’s country is covered with them, making them a large influence on the Alaska Native peoples.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Storytelling in Alaska Native culture is heavily influenced by animals that are a part of the tribes’ everyday lives.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Animals are given the star roles in the stories, both the actor and the main theme.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] The animals symbolize many things such as their beliefs or taboos of a tribe or clan.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] The stories are told about the marking of seasons, when the salmon come into the streams or when the moose lose their antlers.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Animals in story-telling can provide a joyful and humorous experience for the tribe during the winter months.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Animals can play the roles of tricksters in the stories.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Common trickster figures in Native American mythology include the rabbit in the Eastern regions, the coyote and spider in the Plains and the Southwest regions, and the raven in the Pacific Northwest.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Numerous animals appear in myths and legends and they rarely have purely animal characteristics.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] The animals are gifted with the power of speech and human attributes.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] The animals in the stories interact with people and frequently change between human and animal form.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] The stories and themes are constructed around one main animal, like for example the badger, loon, and or beaver.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] These animals are not as popular as the Raven or Crow.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] The raven and or crow are the most popular characters in native folklore.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Amongst the many tribes in Alaska, the raven shares the same meanings, such as the trickster, always getting into trouble, events such as bringing light into the world .
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] The raven symbolizes helping the people and shaping the world.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] These stories all have a main thread running through them about the raven, he is a trickster, but ends up helping the people.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Many different aspects are incorporated into the composition of a traditional Alaska Native story narrative.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] There are tales written with the specific purpose of passing history itself on from one generation to the next.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] In others, pieces of nature that are incorporated can take on a life of their own.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Animals can be deified and worshipped or be cast in the part of a trickster such as the raven or coyote.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] As with any culture, there are stories told to explain a broad spectrum of life‘s aspects, and others are created to express humor alone.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Found within many of the stories that have been recorded, some still told today, are a set of valuable life lessons that are handed down through the relationship of the storyteller and the avid listener.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Woven into a great adventure or a fantastic tale various ideals can be easily recognized within many Alaska Native stories.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] These ideals are painted directly into the heart of the story making it a great lesson for the avid listener.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Such stories are told to teach the young, or to remind someone that has forgotten one of these important principles.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Respecting nature, honoring family and tribe, having faith and trust, or getting along with their fellow men are several that are characteristic and thought important enough to pass on.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Guidance is another prevalent aspect found accompanying the ideals within many Alaska Native stories.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] This guidance offers warnings against apparent evils such as pride, envy, poor decision making, or committing sins.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] In one classic Tlingit tale retold by S.E.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Schlosser and entitled “How selfishness was rewarded”, a woman uses a magical combination of words to summon fish from the ocean late at night.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] She then cooks and consumes this fish while her family sleeps keeping all of the catch for herself.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] Eventually she is caught by her family and is punished for her selfish ways.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] She is magically transformed into an owl, not by her family but, by the magic she had come so accustomed to.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] The tale ends with, "To this day, the plaintive hoot of the owl may be heard in the wilds of Alaska, reminding those who hear it of the price a young girl once paid for her selfishness.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alaska-native-storytelling] The different types of lessons on guidance along with the virtues that are shared and passed along through the tribe’s generations are an important element of the ancient and rich Alaska Native culture and they stories they create.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Captain **Alfred Bulltop Stormalong** was an American folk hero and the subject of numerous nautical-themed tall tales originating in Massachusetts.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Stormalong was said to be a sailor and a giant, some 30 feet (9.1 m) tall; he was the master of a huge clipper ship known in various sources as either the *Courser* or the *Tuscarora*, a ship purportedly so tall that it had hinged masts to avoid catching on the Moon.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] The name of Stormalong first appeared in a cycle of sea shanties that Stan Hugill, in his *Sea Shanties of the Seven Seas*, traces back to African-American folk songs of the 1830s and '40s.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Bearing names like "Mister Stormalong", "Way Stormalong John", and "Yankee John, Stormalong", these sailors' work songs generally featured praise for a deceased seaman and for his benevolent son.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] The tall tales about Stormalong first appeared in the 1911 book *Here's Audacity!* by Frank Shay.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] More tales appeared in the 1933 pamphlet *Old Stormalong Yarns* by C.E.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] New England was where he was beached as a baby, already three fathoms (18 ft) tall.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] According to one telling, he outgrew Cape Cod and moved to Boston, where he signed aboard the first ship that would take him at the age of twelve.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] He had a lifelong rivalry with a Kraken, a huge sea monster from Norse myth; in fact, the Kraken escaped from him in their first encounter, causing a dejected Stormalong to abandon the sea life for life as a farmer somewhere in the Midwest.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Some sources say he had a ship so large that a stable of Arabian horses were aboard for his crew to get from one end of the ship to the other.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Among other things, the ship Alfred was best said to have drilled the course of the Panama Canal by slamming into the Panamanian coast, and to have gotten stuck in the English Channel, which required the crew to grease the ship's hull with soap.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] The soap combined with the scraping of the hull against the Gray Cliffs of Dover turned them bright white.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] As Stormalong grew older, he eventually encountered the Kraken again, this time successfully drawing the beast into a whirlpool from which it never escaped.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] The aged Stormalong won the race by several miles, but the stress of handling the wheel through the difficult Atlantic crossing killed him.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Stormalong was buried at sea, and Davy Jones himself opened his famous locker to accept Stormalong's body.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Another ending to his life is as follows: While Stormalong was on his Caribbean adventures, he passed by Florida, seeing that there was a tremendous hurricane that tore through his ship.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Ships sailing nearby were being tossed around by the heavy waves.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Stormalong went overboard and piled as many boats as he could onto his ship.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] When the storm finally wound down, the sailors were dropped back off at Florida.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] After that, he went back on board, unfurling the sails of his ship, seeing if they could be repaired.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] A great wind, the last blow of the hurricane, hit the sails, lifting Stormalong and his ship into the sky.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] A third ending to his life takes advantage of the inference that, being a giant, Alfred Bulltop Stormalong was an enormous eater.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] It describes a time when his hunger was greater than usual and led him to eat so much food (one variant cites a breakfast of six sharks; it is not definitely known what other variants exist) that he suffered terminal indigestion, causing his magnificent appetite to finish him.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/ambassador-clipper] William Walker built *Ambassador* at Lavender Dry Dock in London.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/ambassador-clipper] Though considered a fast ship, *Ambassador* was said to be "very cranky and overmasted".
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/ambassador-clipper] Her first passage to the UK from Fuzhou came during the Tea Race of 1870 under Captain Duggan and took 115 days, a mediocre performance; that same year the fastest tea passage, also from Fuzhou, was made by the clipper *Lahloo* in just 98 days.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/ambassador-clipper] *Ambassador*'s fastest passage between China and England was 108 days, in 1872.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/ambassador-clipper] The wreck is now reduced to a skeletal frame.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/andrew-jackson-clipper] The ***Andrew Jackson*** was a 1,679-registered-ton medium clipper built by the firm of Irons & Grinnell in Mystic, Connecticut in 1855.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/andrew-jackson-clipper] The vessel was designed for the shipping firm of J.H.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/andrew-jackson-clipper] Brower & Co. to carry cargo intended for sale to participants in the California Gold Rush.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/andrew-jackson-clipper] The ship was 220 feet (67 m) in length, had a beam of 41 ft., 2 in., and a draft 22 ft., 3 in.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/andrew-jackson-clipper] The vessel was described as "a very handsome, well-designed ship.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/andrew-jackson-clipper] This was one of only three 89-day runs performed by square-rigged ships driving from New York City to California.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/andrew-jackson-clipper] The other two runs were both posted by *Flying Cloud*.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/andrew-jackson-clipper] *Flying Cloud*'s fastest New York-to-California run had taken 89 days and 8 hours; *Andrew Jackson*'s run was, by four hours, widely acclaimed in the newspapers as the fastest in history.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/andrew-jackson-clipper] Some clipper ship authorities, including Howe and Matthews, assert that *Andrew Jackson* did not actually set the record described above.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/andrew-jackson-clipper] They concede, however, that this medium clipper, perhaps not naturally as fast as *Flying Cloud*, achieved a remarkable passage as the result of a combination of hard driving by the captain and favorable winds.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/andrew-jackson-clipper] However, after careful scrutiny of the logbooks, one author, Carl C.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/andrew-jackson-clipper] Cutler, concludes that a case can be made for either *Flying Cloud* or *Andrew Jackson* holding the record.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/andrew-jackson-clipper] Some will consider the passage from pilot-to-pilot as the appropriate indicator of fastest sailing performance around Cape Horn.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/andrew-jackson-clipper] *Flying Cloud* holds the record time for a passage anchor-to-anchor from New York to San Francisco, of 89 days 8 hours, while *Andrew Jackson'*s completed passage anchor-to-anchor may have been as long as 89 days 20 hours.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] The **Angel of Hadley** is the central character in a possibly apocryphal tale combining the execution of Charles I in England, King Philip's War and Hadley, Massachusetts.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] According to the tale Colonel William Goffe, who was wanted for his role in the regicide, was hiding in Hadley when it was attacked by Indians in 1675 or 1676.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] Goffe, by then an aging figure, is said to have come out of his hiding to lead the local residents in the successful defense of their community against the attack.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] The story contains many kernels of truth, although some appear to have been deliberately obscured by chroniclers of the time (notably Increase Mather) in order to protect Goffe.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] There is strong evidence that he was in Hadley at the times of various attacks on Hadley, and many of the political and military leaders involved, as well as chroniclers of the time, knew of his presence and sympathized with his plight.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] There are inconsistent accounts about *which* attack he would have been involved in, and uncertainty about the location of troops that are conventionally claimed to have fought off the attackers.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] King Philip's War broke out in southern New England in 1675 following disputes between Metacom (called King Phillip by the English) the leader of the Wampanoag tribe, and the English colonies.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] The war raged across southern New England in 1675, and numerous English frontier towns were attacked.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] According to the legend, one such attack was made against Hadley, Massachusetts, most commonly described as occurring on September 1, 1675.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] With all hope seemingly lost, a white-bearded man with a powerful bearing and wielding an old sword suddenly appeared.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] He organized the town militia before leading them to victory against the more numerous natives.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] William Goffe (born between 1613 and 1618) was a Parliamentarian military officer during the English Civil War of the 1640s, rising to Lieutenant-General.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] He was one of 59 signatories to the death warrant of King Charles I in 1649, and continued to play an influential role in the English government during The Protectorate rule of Oliver Cromwell in the 1650s.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] In 1660 Charles II was restored to the throne.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] Although many opponents of crown rule were granted amnesty, the regicides were specifically excluded.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] Goffe and his father-in-law Edward Whalley, another regicide, fled to New England.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] They were well known to Increase Mather and Daniel Gookin among others, and were able to move freely in Boston until it was known that Charles II was likely to order their arrest.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] Goffe and Whalley fled to the New Haven Colony, where John Davenport, a sympathetic minister, sheltered them for a time, and the political leadership disclaimed knowledge of their whereabouts.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] It is likely that Davenport connected them with John Russell, the minister at Hadley, Massachusetts, where the two men eventually settled into a highly secluded life.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] Only a small number of people are believed to have known where they were.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] Goffe was able to exchange letters with his wife in England through the mediation of Increase Mather, an influential Boston minister, and Daniel Gookin, a political leader in the Massachusetts government, is known to have overseen some of their financial affairs.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] Edward Whalley is believed to have died in roughly 1675; Goffe reported that he had suffered a stroke and was not in good condition.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] Goffe is assumed to have been in Hadley during some of the attacks made on the town during the war; however, by the later months of 1676 letters he sent indicated that he had relocated to the Hartford, Connecticut area, where he is assumed to have died some years later.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] There were two supposed attacks on Hadley that have been connected to the legend.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] The first occurred on September 1, 1675, and the second on June 12, 1676.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] Increase Mather, who wrote one of the first accounts of the war, described the September 1 event as an "alarm", implying that there was no actual attack, merely an urgent notice that an attack had taken place somewhere nearby.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] He gave a slightly more detailed account of the June 12 action, in which he implied (but did not explicitly state) that militia troops from Connecticut who had been stationed nearby were instrumental in fending off the Indian attack.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] There is some uncertainty about where the Connecticut troops were on the day of the attack.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] They had been sent north as part of a planned sweep of the Connecticut River valley, to be performed in conjunction with Massachusetts troops that were en route from the east.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] They were known to have arrived at Hadley a few days before June 12, but there is significant evidence that on the day of the attack they were across the river in Northampton.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] A significant number of people involved in the events surrounding the June 12 action, and the later reporting of it, had knowledge of Goffe's presence in Hadley.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] Major John Talcott, who led the Connecticut forces, was a brother-in-law of John Russell, who was sheltering them.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] The governor of Massachusetts was John Leverett, who had served in the Parliamentary Army during the civil war, and is known to have visited Hadley during the time Goffe and Whalley were there.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] Increase Mather, as one of the intermediaries handling their letters, wrote one of the most important early accounts of the war.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] The political leaders of the Connecticut Colony at the time were Robert Treat and William Leete, who had been leaders in the New Haven Colony when Goffe and Whalley passed through there.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] Historian Douglas Wilson suggests that at least some of these people, all of whom were sympathetic to Goffe, may have acted, either independently or in concert, to cover up any role Goffe may have had in the June 12 action.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] There are no significant records of the action in surviving Massachusetts and Connecticut records.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] Wilson notes that there is a letter, discovered in 1870, from John Russell to Increase Mather, dated 1677, after Mather's publication of his history.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] Russell wrote "I find nothing considerable mistaken in your history.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] That which I most fear in the matter is lest Mr.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] B or some of Connecticut should clash with ours and contradict each other in the story as to matter of fact." Wilson concludes that "Mr.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] B" was probably Gershom Bulkeley, a political opponent of the Puritans who was part of Talcott's force.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] The first publication of the angel tale was apparently in the late 18th century by Thomas Hutchinson in his *History of the Province of Massachusetts Bay*, in which he describes the tale as having originated with John Leverett's family.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] Subsequent historians picked up and elaborated on the story.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] Later in the 19th century historians began to examine the story more critically, with George Sheldon specifically debunking it in 1874.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] Because of the inconsistencies raised by Sheldon, many 20th-century historians have accepted that the tale does not describe an event that actually happened, and it has been widely propagated as not having occurred.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] Douglas Wilson carefully reassessed the available evidence, concluding in his 1987 paper on the matter that it *might* have taken place, and that the event, and Goffe's involvement in it, were covered up by Goffe's protectors.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] The legend furnished ideas used by Sir Walter Scott in *Peveril of the Peak* and by James Fenimore Cooper in *The Wept of Wish-ton-Wish*.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] It is also a likely source for "The Gray Champion", a Nathaniel Hawthorne short story that features an elderly Puritan man who brandishes a sword in defense of his people.
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] Jack Dunn wrote The Diary of General William Goffe published in 1982 which was syndicated in The Valley Advocate in weekly installments as "The Angel of Hadley".
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] Goffe is portrayed as The Angel of Hadley in Channel 4's *New Worlds* (2014), the sequel to 2008's *The Devil's Whore* (in North America, *The Devil's Mistress*).
[src:alfred-bulltop-stormalong/angel-of-hadley] A fictionalised version of the story forms part of Robert Harris's 2022 novel *Act of Oblivion*, in which Goffe is one of the main protagonists.
